{
    "analysis": "The fault-identification step has been completed. Using global thresholds computed from full-series data and filtering to the incident window (2020-05-23 03:30–04:00+08), we detected sustained, high-severity anomalies across multiple disk/page I/O KPIs. The top affected series are node-level OS metrics (Page_pi, Disk_rd_ios, Disk_io_util, Page_po, Disk_wr_ios, Disk_rd_kbs) on several OS nodes—most notably os_020, os_018, os_019, os_008, os_006. Many of these series show anomaly_count == window_count and longest consecutive anomalous streaks equal to the full window with earliest anomalies at 2020-05-23 03:30:00+08, indicating persistent I/O problems starting at the window start. Some DB KPIs are also anomalous but with much lower numeric severity compared to the OS disk metrics. At this stage we have strong evidence of node-level disk I/O faults beginning at 03:30+08, but multiple OS nodes are affected. We must now aggregate the detected faults by component to determine the predominant faulty node(s) (the most likely root-cause component(s)) and report earliest occurrence times and severity per node. Trace-level anomalies can be consulted afterwards if multiple components remain tied.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the previously stored fault-detection table (kernel variable), aggregate faults by cmdb_id and return a compact table (limit top 20 rows) with these columns: cmdb_id, faulty_kpi_count (number of (cmdb_id,kpi) pairs that passed the fault filter), earliest_fault_ts (minimum earliest_anomaly_ts across its KPIs), latest_fault_ts (maximum earliest_anomaly_ts), max_severity (maximum severity among its KPIs), avg_severity, total_anomalous_points (sum of anomaly_count), total_window_points (sum of window_count), percent_anomalous = total_anomalous_points/total_window_points, and top_kpis (comma-separated list of up to 8 KPI names with highest severity for that cmdb_id). Also return a one-line summary/count of how many distinct cmdb_id components were found faulty and how many of them are OS vs docker vs db (based on name prefixes 'os_', 'docker_', 'db_'). Keep outputs compact and limit rows to top 20 sorted by faulty_kpi_count desc then max_severity desc." }

High-severity, sustained node-level I/O and paging anomalies started at the incident window start (03:30+08) on os_008; mapped to the closest provided reason category as a CPU-related fault (high iowait).

